              "id": "glog-c63b9801-4186-4b60-9e53-caf7a15e5106",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"An Insecure Cipher Mode of Operation Was Utilized\" in C++ refers to the use of cryptographic algorithms in a mode that does not provide adequate security guarantees. In particular, using a non-authenticated encryption mode can lead to vulnerabilities such as replay attacks, tampering, and other forms of cryptographic attacks. AEAD (Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data) modes, such as GCM (Galois/Counter Mode) or CCM (Counter with CBC-MAC), are recommended to ensure both confidentiality and integrity of the data.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Use AEAD Modes**: Always use authenticated encryption modes like AES-GCM or AES-CCM to ensure both confidentiality and integrity.\n2. **Avoid ECB Mode**: Never use ECB (Electronic Codebook) mode as it is insecure for most applications.\n3. **Use Strong Keys**: Ensure that cryptographic keys are generated securely and have sufficient entropy.\n4. **Keep Libraries Updated**: Use the latest versions of cryptographic libraries to benefit from security patches and improvements.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nBelow is an example of how to use AES-GCM in C++ using the OpenSSL library:\n\n```cpp\n#include <openssl/evp.h>\n#include <openssl/rand.h>\n#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n\nbool encrypt(const std::vector<unsigned char>& plaintext, const std::vector<unsigned char>& key,\n             const std::vector<unsigned char>& iv, std::vector<unsigned char>& ciphertext,\n             std::vector<unsigned char>& tag) {\n    EVP_CIPHER_CTX* ctx = EVP_CIPHER_CTX_new();\n    if (!ctx) return false;\n\n    if (EVP_EncryptInit_ex(ctx, EVP_aes_256_gcm(), NULL, NULL, NULL) != 1) {\n        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    if (EVP_EncryptInit_ex(ctx, NULL, NULL, key.data(), iv.data()) != 1) {\n        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    int len;\n    ciphertext.resize(plaintext.size());\n    if (EVP_EncryptUpdate(ctx, ciphertext.data(), &len, plaintext.data(), plaintext.size()) != 1) {\n        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    int ciphertext_len = len;\n    if (EVP_EncryptFinal_ex(ctx, ciphertext.data() + len, &len) != 1) {\n        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n        return false;\n    }\n    ciphertext_len += len;\n\n    ciphertext.resize(ciphertext_len);\n    tag.resize(16);\n    if (EVP_CIPHER_CTX_ctrl(ctx, EVP_CTRL_GCM_GET_TAG, 16, tag.data()) != 1) {\n        EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n        return false;\n    }\n\n    EVP_CIPHER_CTX_free(ctx);\n    return true;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    std::vector<unsigned char> key(32); // 256-bit key\n    std::vector<unsigned char> iv(12);  // 96-bit IV\n    std::vector<unsigned char> plaintext = {'H', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o', ' ', 'W', 'o', 'r', 'l', 'd'};\n    std::vector<unsigned char> ciphertext;\n    std::vector<unsigned char> tag;\n\n    if (!RAND_bytes(key.data(), key.size()) || !RAND_bytes(iv.data(), iv.size())) {\n        std::cerr << \"Error generating random bytes for key/iv\" << std::endl;\n        return 1;\n    }\n\n    if (encrypt(plaintext, key, iv, ciphertext, tag)) {\n        std::cout << \"Encryption successful!\" << std::endl;\n    } else {\n        std::cerr << \"Encryption failed!\" << std::endl;\n    }\n\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\n- OpenSSL\n\nTo compile the above code, you need to link against the OpenSSL library. You can do this by using the following command:\n\n```bash\ng++ -o encrypt_example encrypt_example.cpp -lssl -lcrypto\n```\n\n### Relevant Links\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
