              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nIn C++ programming, storing sensitive information such as tokens, API keys, or passwords directly in the source code is a common security vulnerability. This practice can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is exposed, as these secrets can be easily extracted by malicious actors. This vulnerability is particularly concerning in environments where the source code is shared or stored in version control systems.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Environment Variables**: Store sensitive information in environment variables instead of hardcoding them in the source code.\n2. **Configuration Files**: Use configuration files that are not included in the source code repository. Ensure these files are encrypted or access-controlled.\n3. **Secret Management Tools**: Utilize secret management tools or services (e.g., HashiCorp Vault, AWS Secrets Manager) to securely store and access sensitive information.\n4. **Access Control**: Limit access to the source code and configuration files to only those who need it.\n5. **Code Reviews**: Regularly conduct code reviews to ensure that sensitive information is not being stored in the source code.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nBelow is an example of how to refactor code to avoid storing a token directly in the source code. The original code might look like this:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nint main() {\n    // Vulnerable: Token is hardcoded in the source code\n    std::string token = \"3554e37ca417001fce0154e047e7878b18c5ee0e587dd94bf764a4846e500a403f5e\";\n    std::cout << \"Token: \" << token << std::endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nRefactored code using environment variables:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <cstdlib>\n\nint main() {\n    // Secure: Token is retrieved from an environment variable\n    const char* token = std::getenv(\"MY_SECURE_TOKEN\");\n    if (token == nullptr) {\n        std::cerr << \"Error: Token not found in environment variables.\" << std::endl;\n        return 1;\n    }\n    std::cout << \"Token: \" << token << std::endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example does not require any additional library dependencies beyond the C++ Standard Library.\n\n### Relevant Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Secrets Management](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Top Ten: A3:2017-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
